Let \Ves{physical} be an Earley set as produced by \Marpa{},
and let \Vves{virtual} be \Ves{physical} with its Leo memoized
items restored.
We will call \Ves{physical} a \dfn{physical} Earley set, and
we will call \Vves{virtual} a \dfn{virtual} Earley set
(type \type{VES}).

To show how an physical Earley set is restored,
we will need a few definitions.
Because a LIM has exactly one link pair,
\begin{gather}
\PreviousLink{\Vlim{$\ell$}} \defined \text{the previous link of \Vlim{$\ell$}, and} \\
\Source{\Vlim{$\ell$}} \defined \text{the source EIM link of \Vlim{$\ell$}}.
\end{gather}
and expect both \var{PreviousLink} and \var{Source} to be functions.
Let
\begin{align}
\label{e-unhide-a}
& \mymathop{Unhide}(\Lambda, \Veim{base}) \defined \emptyset \\
\intertext{and, when $\Vlim{link} \neq \Lambda$, let}
\label{e-unhide-b}
&
\begin{aligned}
& \mymathop{Unhide}(\Vlim{link}, \Veim{base}) \defined \\
& \quad \left\lbrace \;\;
\begin{gathered}
\mymathop{Unhide}(\PreviousLink{\Vlim{link}}, \Veim{new-base}) \\
\qquad \cup \quad \set{\Veim{new-base}} \\
\text{where $\Veim{new-base} = \left[ \Next{\Vdr{link}}, \Vorig{link} \right]_\type{EIM}$} \\
\land \;\; [ \Vdr{link}, \Vsym{link}, \Vorig{link} ] = \Vlim{link}
\end{gathered}
\;\; \right\rbrace
\end{aligned}
\end{align}
In \Eref{e-unhide-b},
\Veim{new-base} is created with a single link pair,
$[ \Source{\Vlim{link}}, \Veim{base} ]$.

Then the set of memoized EIMs in \Ves{i}, $\mymathop{Memoized}(\Ves{i})$ is
\begin{equation*}
\left\lbrace
\begin{aligned}
& \Veim{virtual} : \\
& \qquad
\begin{aligned}
         & \Veim{physical} \in \Ves{i} \\
\land \;\; & \left[ (\Vlim{link}, \Veim{base}) \right] \in \LinkPairs{\Veim{physical}} \\
\land \;\; & \Veim{virtual} \in \mymathop{Unhide}(\Vlim{link}, \Veim{base}).
\end{aligned}
\end{aligned}
\right\rbrace
\end{equation*}
Then, \Vves{i}, the virtual Earley set corresponding to \Ves{i}, is
\begin{equation*}
\Ves{i} \;\; \cup \;\; \mymathop{Memoized}(\Ves{i}).
\end{equation*}

